# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-physical-society
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A **501(c) organization** is a nonprofit organization in the federal law of the United States according to Internal Revenue Code (26 U.S.C. § 501(c)).
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Such organizations are exempt from some federal income taxes.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Sections 503 through 505 set out the requirements for obtaining such exemptions.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Many states refer to Section 501(c) for definitions of organizations exempt from state taxation as well.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] 501(c) organizations can receive unlimited contributions from individuals, corporations, and unions.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] For example, a nonprofit organization may be tax-exempt under section 501(c)(3) if its primary activities are charitable, religious, educational, scientific, literary, testing for public safety, fostering amateur sports competition, or preventing cruelty to children or animals.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] According to the IRS Publication 557, in the *Organization Reference Chart* section, the following is an exact list of 501(c) organization types (29 in total) and their corresponding descriptions.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c) organization is subject to tax on its unrelated business income.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] For most organizations, an organization's activity generates unrelated business income if it is regularly carried on and it is not substantially related to furthering the exempt purpose of the organization.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Disposal of donated goods valued over $2,500, or acceptance of goods worth over $5,000 may trigger special filing and record-keeping requirements.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c) organization must maintain proper records and file certain annual or special-purpose tax returns, e.g., 26 U.S.C. § 6033 and 26 U.S.C. § 6050L.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Prior to 2008, an annual return was not generally required from an exempt organization with less than $25,000 in gross income yearly.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Since 2008, most organizations whose annual gross receipts are less than $50,000 must file an annual information return known as Form 990-N.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Form 990-N, Form 990, Form 990-EZ, and Form 990-PF must be submitted electronically.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Failure to file required returns such as Form 990 (Return of Organization Exempt From Income Tax) may result in fines of up to $250,000 per year.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Exempt or political organizations, excluding churches or similar religious entities, must make their returns, reports, notices, and exempt applications available for public inspection.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Form 4506-A also allows the public inspection or photocopying access to Form 1023 "Application for Recognition of Exemption" or Form 1024, Form 8871 "Political Organization Notice of Section 527 Status", and Form 8872 "Political Organization Report of Contribution and Expenditures".
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Internet access to many organizations' 990 and some other forms are available through GuideStar.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Failure to file such timely returns and to make other specific information available to the public also is prohibited.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Between 2010 and 2017 the IRS revoked the nonprofit status of more than 760,000 nonprofit organizations for failing to file the 990 form.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The 501(c)(3) exemption also applies for any unincorporated community chest, fund, cooperating association, or foundation that is organized and operated exclusively for those purposes.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] There are also supporting organizations—often referred to in shorthand form as "Friends of" organizations.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] 26 U.S.C. § 170, provides a deduction, for federal income tax purposes, for some donors who make charitable contributions to most types of 501(c)(3) organizations, among others.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Organizations described in section 501(c)(3) are prohibited from conducting political campaign activities to intervene in elections to public office.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] On the other hand, public charities (but not private foundations) may conduct a limited amount of lobbying to influence legislation.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Although the law states that "No substantial part..." of a public charity's activities can go to lobbying, charities may register for a 501(h) election allowing them to lawfully conduct lobbying activities as long as their financial expenditure does not exceed a specified amount.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] 501(c)(3) organizations risk loss of tax exempt status if any of these rules are violated.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to conduct some or all of its charitable activities outside the United States.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Donors' contributions to a 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible only if the contribution is for the use of the 501(c)(3) organization, and that the 501(c)(3) organization is not merely serving as an agent or conduit of a foreign charitable organization.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A **501(c)(4) organization** is a social welfare organization, such as a civic organization or a neighborhood association.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] An organization is considered by the IRS to be operated exclusively for the promotion of social welfare if it is primarily engaged in promoting the common good and general welfare of the people of the community.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Net earnings must be exclusively used for charitable, educational, or recreational purposes.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] 501(c)(4)s are similar to 501(c)(5)s and 501(c)(6)s in that the organizations may inform the public on controversial subjects and attempt to influence legislation relevant to its program.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Unlike 501(c)(3) organizations, they may also participate in political campaigns and elections, as long as their primary activity is the promotion of social welfare and related to the organization's purpose.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The income tax exemption for 501(c)(4) organizations applies to most of their operations, but income spent on political activities—generally the advocacy of a particular candidate in an election—is taxable.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] An "action" organization generally qualifies as a 501(c)(4) organization.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] An "action" organization is one whose activities substantially include, or are exclusively, direct or grassroots lobbying related to advocacy for or against legislation or proposing, supporting, or opposing legislation that is related to its purpose.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(4) organization may directly or indirectly support or oppose a candidate for public office as long as such activities are not a substantial amount of its activities.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(4) organization that lobbies must register with the Clerk of the House if it lobbies members of the House or their staff.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Likewise, a 501(c)(4) organization must register with the Secretary of the Senate if it lobbies members of the Senate or their staff.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] In addition, the 501(c)(4) organization must either inform its members the amount it spends on lobbying or pay a proxy tax to the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Lobbying expenses and political expenses are not deductible as business expenses.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Wisconsin Right to Life, Inc.*, in which the Supreme Court struck down the part of the McCain-Feingold Act that prohibited 501(c)(4)s, 501(c)(5)s, and 501(c)(6)s from broadcasting electioneering communications.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The Act defined an electioneering communication as a communication that mentions a candidate's name 60 days before a primary or 30 days before a general election.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Contributions to 501(c)(4) organizations are not tax-deductible as charitable donations unless the organization is either a volunteer fire department or a veterans organization.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Dues or contributions to 501(c)(4) organizations may be deductible as a business expense under IRC 162, although amounts paid for intervention or participation in any political campaign, direct lobbying, grass roots lobbying, and contact with certain federal officials are not deductible.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] If a 501(c)(4) engages in a substantial number of these activities, then only the amount of dues or contributions that can be attributed to other activities may be deductible as a business expense.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The organization must provide a notice to its members containing a reasonable estimate of the amount related to lobbying and political campaign expenditures, or else it is subject to a proxy tax on its lobbying and political campaign expenditures.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] It must also state that contributions to the organization are not deductible as charitable contributions during fundraising.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(4) organization is not required to disclose their donors publicly, with the exception of organizations that make independent expenditures as of 2018.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The former complete lack of disclosure led to extensive use of the 501(c)(4) provisions for organizations that are actively involved in lobbying, and has become controversial.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Criticized as "dark money", spending from these organizations on political advertisements has exceeded spending from Super PACs.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Spending by organizations that do not disclose their donors increased from less than $5.2 million in 2006 to well over $300 million during the 2012 election season.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The origins of 501(c)(4) organizations date back to the Revenue Act of 1913, which created a new group of tax-exempt organizations dedicated to social welfare in a precursor to what is now Internal Revenue Code Section 501(c)(4).
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The Protecting Americans from Tax Hikes Act of 2015 introduced a new requirement on 501(c)(4) organizations.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Within 60 days of the organization's formation, a 501(c)(4) organization is required to file Form 8976 with the Internal Revenue Service as notification that it is operating as a section 501(c)(4) organization.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The Internal Revenue Service will acknowledge receipt of the notification, but the acknowledgment is not a determination that the organization qualifies for section 501(c)(4) tax-exempt status.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(4) organization is not required to send the notification if the organization was formed on or before July 8, 2016, and it either applied for a determination letter using Form 1024 or filed a Form 990 between December 19, 2015, and July 8, 2016.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] As of January 2018, the application for recognition of exemption as a 501(c)(4) organization is a new form, Form 1024-A, rather than Form 1024.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] In 2017 revocations of 501(c)(4) groups comprised 58% which usually is only 15% of the total nonprofits which have their tax status revoked by the IRS for their failure to file Form 990.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A **501(c)(5) organization** is a labor organization, an agricultural organization, or a horticultural organization.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Labor unions, county fairs, and flower societies are examples of these types of groups.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Labor union organizations were a primary benefactor of this organization type, dating to the 19th century.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] According to the Internal Revenue Service, a 501(c)(5) organization has a duty of providing service to its members first.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The organization's benefits may not inure to a specific member, but the rules for inurement vary among the three different types of organizations under this segment.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(5) organization can make unlimited corporate, individual, or union contributions.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A labor organization may pay benefits to its members because paying benefits improves all members' shared working conditions.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] An agricultural organization can provide financial assistance to its members in order to improve the conditions of those engaged in agricultural pursuits generally.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Members can benefit in incidental ways from the organization's exempt activities as long as the benefits are available to all persons.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The first exemption for labor organizations from corporate income tax was enacted as part of the Payne–Aldrich Tariff Act of 1909.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The Revenue Act of 1913 excluded "labor, agricultural, or horticultural organizations" from income tax liability.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Much like 501(c)(4) and 501(c)(6) organizations, 501(c)(5) organizations may also perform some political activities.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] 501(c)(5) organizations are allowed to attempt to influence legislation that is related to the common union interests of its members.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] 501(c)(5) organizations can receive unlimited contributions from corporations, individuals, and labor unions.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The names and addresses of contributors are not required to be made available for public inspection.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] All other information, including the amount of contributions, the description of noncash contributions, and any other information, is required to be made available for public inspection unless it clearly identifies the contributor.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A union membership dues paid to a 501(c)(5) organization are generally an ordinary and necessary business expense.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The membership dues are tax-deductible in full unless a substantial part of the 501(c)(5) organization's activities consists of political activity, in which case a tax deduction is allowed only for the portion of membership dues that are for other activities.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The Federal Election Commission is required to enforce this provision based on a federal court decision in 2018.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A **501(c)(6) organization** is a business league, a chamber of commerce like the U.S.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A business league may qualify if it is an association of persons having a common business interest, whose purpose is to promote the common business interest and whose activities improve business conditions rather than actually conduct the business itself.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Members of the organization must be of the same trade, business, occupation, or profession in order to qualify.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A local chamber of commerce or board of trade could qualify for similar reasons except that they may promote the common economic interests of all the commercial enterprises in a given trade or community.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] In order to qualify for a tax-exemption under section 501(c)(6), the organization must specify that it seeks to promote and improve business condition for a specific type of business.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Improving business conditions for *all* types of businesses is not generally qualifying.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Similarly, providing a service for a specific type of business is also not typically qualifying, as that would usually be more of a commercial enterprise.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] For example, the service of managing health insurance plans for its member businesses is often a commercial enterprise if it is not substantially related to improving the business conditions for specific lines of businesses.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] An association that promotes the common interests of certain hobbyists would not qualify because the Internal Revenue Service does not consider hobbies to be activities conducted as businesses.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] An organization whose primary activity is advertising the products or services of its members does not qualify because the organization is performing a service for its members rather than promoting common interests.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] If an organization's primary activity is advertising the products or services of its members' industry as a whole, however, the organization will generally qualify if it also performs other services for its members.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Much like 501(c)(4) and 501(c)(5) organizations, 501(c)(6) organizations may also perform some political activities.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] 501(c)(6) organizations are allowed to attempt to influence legislation that is related to the common business interests of its members.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(6) organization may receive unlimited contributions from corporations, individuals, and labor unions.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The names and addresses of contributors are not required to be made available for public inspection, with the exception of a 501(c)(6) organization that makes independent expenditures.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] All other information, including the amount of contributions, the description of non-cash contributions, and any other information, is required to be made available for public inspection unless it clearly identifies the contributor.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Chamber of Commerce is a large political spender, and Freedom Partners used its status as a 501(c)(6) organization to raise and distribute over $250 million during the 2012 election campaigns without disclosing its donors.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The group's existence was not publicly known until nearly a year after the election.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A business's membership dues paid to a 501(c)(6) organization are generally an ordinary and necessary business expense.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The membership dues are tax-deductible in full unless a substantial part of the 501(c)(6) organization's activities consists of political activity, in which case a tax deduction is allowed only for the portion of membership dues that are for other activities.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The predecessor of IRC 501(c)(6) was enacted as part of the Revenue Act of 1913 likely due to a U.S.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Chamber of Commerce request for an exemption for nonprofit "civic" and "commercial" organizations, which resulted in IRC 501(c)(4) for nonprofit "civic" organizations and IRC 501(c)(6) for nonprofit "commercially-oriented" organizations.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The Revenue Act of 1928 amended the statute to include real estate boards.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] In 1966, professional football leagues were added to the described organizations.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] IRC 501(c)(6) amendment was enacted in 1966 to ensure that a professional football league's exemption would not be jeopardized because it administered a players' pension fund.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Additionally, a professional sports league's exemption is not to be jeopardized because its primary source of revenue is the sale of television broadcasting rights to its games because the broadcasting of games increases public awareness of the sport.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] In 2013, Senator Tom Coburn introduced legislation to disallow a tax exemption for the National Football League, the Professional Golfers' Association of America, and other professional sports organizations.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Coburn estimated the tax exemption cost $100 million, but he said he could not get other members of Congress to support the legislation.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A **501(c)(7) organization** is a social or recreational club that is organized for pleasure, recreation, and other nonprofitable purposes.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Members must share interests and have a common goal directed toward pleasure and recreation, and the organization must provide opportunities for personal contact among members.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The organization's facilities and services must be open to its members and their guests only.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The organization must be a club of individuals, and no individual may derive profit from the organization's net earnings.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Examples include college alumni associations; college fraternities or college sororities operating chapter houses for students; country clubs; amateur sport clubs; supper clubs that provide a meeting place, library, and dining room for members; hobby clubs; and garden clubs.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A substantial amount of the 501(c)(7) organization's activities must be related to social and recreational activities for its members.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] No more than 35 percent of its gross receipts may derive from non-members, and no more than 15 percent of its gross receipts is permitted to come from use of its facilities or services by the general public.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] An organization that exceeds these limits may lose its 501(c)(7) status.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Similarly, if at least 75 percent of a group using club facilities are members of the organization, the Internal Revenue Service will assume the nonmembers are the guests of the member, and the revenue is deemed to be derived from the member.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] It is the responsibility of the organization to maintain these records.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] If the organization does not keep sufficient records to link revenue to a member, the Internal Revenue Service assumes the revenue came from a nonmember.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The organization is subject to Unrelated Business Income Tax for the revenue derived from nonmember use of its facilities and services, less allowable deductions.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] If the organization sells assets that were previously used for recreational or social purposes, the proceeds are considered related business income as long as the proceeds are reinvested in the organization.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Public use of the organization's facilities must be minimal, generally either less than $2,500 per year or less than five percent of its total gross receipts from normal and usual activities of the club.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(7) organization cannot have a written policy of discriminating on the basis of race, color, or religion.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Nevertheless, a 501(c)(7) organization is permitted to limit its members to a particular religion in order to further the teachings of that religion.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] An auxiliary of a 501(c)(8) fraternal benefit society that limits membership to members of a particular religion is allowed to do so as well.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Having written policies that limit its membership by ethnic origin and gender would not jeopardize the organization's tax-exempt status.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Congress justified the tax-exemption with the reasoning that the members join to provide themselves with recreational or social organization without further tax consequences, similar as if they had paid for the benefits directly.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Tax-exemption was available for organizations operated exclusively for pleasure, recreation, and other nonprofitable purposes.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] In 1969, Congress passed a law stating that social and recreational clubs were permitted to engage in some unrelated business income, subject to income tax.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A **501(c)(8) organization** is a fraternal benefit society.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The society must have members of a similar calling, recreation, or profession, or members who work together to accomplish a worthy goal.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The members have associated themselves in order to help each other and to promote the common cause.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The society must have written documentation of its eligibility standards for membership, classes of membership, a process of admission, and rights and privileges of members.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The members must have a common bond, which may be based on religious beliefs, gender, occupation, ethnicity, or shared values.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The society must have a supreme governing body and subordinate lodges into which members are elected, initiated, or admitted in accordance with its laws.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The supreme governing body should be composed of delegates elected directly by members or intermediate assemblies.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The society must offer benefits to members, which may include life insurance, medical insurance, scholarships, educational programs, travel opportunities, and discount programs.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Revenue generated from providing benefits to non-members must be insubstantial to the society and may be taxable as unrelated business income.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Fraternal benefit societies trace their lineage back through mutual benefit societies, friendly societies and eventually to medieval guilds.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Many fraternal benefit societies were founded to serve the needs of immigrants and other under-served groups who shared common bonds of religion, ethnicity, gender, occupation or shared values.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Section 38 of the Payne–Aldrich Tariff Act of 1909 was the first law to provide a tax-exemption for fraternal beneficiary societies.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The tax-exemption was later codified as section 501(c)(8) with the Internal Revenue Code of 1954.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Similar to 501(c)(8) organizations, 501(c)(10) organizations are also fraternal societies, orders, or associations operating under the lodge system, but 501(c)(10) organizations do not offer life, sick, accident, or other benefits.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] 501(c)(10) organizations devote net earnings exclusively to religious, charitable, scientific, literary, educational, and fraternal purposes.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A **501(c)(13)** organization is a certain type of cemetery company.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] There are two primary types of eligible cemetery companies.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A mutual cemetery company must be either "owned by and operated exclusively for the benefit of its lot owners who hold such lots for bona fide burial purposes and not for the purpose of resale" or engages in the burial of impoverished people performing similar charitable activities.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A nonprofit cemetery corporation must be incorporated solely for the purpose of the burial or the cremation of bodies and no part of its net earnings inures to the benefit of any private shareholder or individual.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Any net gain by the cemetery must be devoted to certain cemetery functions, such as the cemetery's operations, maintenance, and improvements; acquisition of cemetery property; and investment of the net gain in order to provide additional income for cemetery functions.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Net gains are not allowed to be distributed to individuals.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A perpetual care fund that is used by a profit-making cemetery to maintain cemetery properties and burial lots is not eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] On the other hand, a nonprofit organization may have a perpetual care fund without jeopardizing its exemption under Section 501(c)(13).
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A cemetery that owns or operates a morgue, whether on its own grounds or elsewhere, is not eligible under 501(c)(13) because the Internal Revenue Service does not consider mortuary services necessarily incident to burial purposes.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The provision of traditional burial services that directly support and maintain basic tenets and beliefs of a religion regarding burial of its members" may still be eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A cemetery that buries animals is not eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] A cemetery company wishing to be recognized under Section 501(c)(13) needs to prepare and file Form 1024 with the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Charitable contributions to a 501(c)(13) organization are tax-deductible to the donor.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Payments for perpetual care of a particular lot or a particular crypt are not considered tax-deductible charitable contributions.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Payments made as part of the purchase price of a burial lot or crypt are not considered tax-deductible charitable contributions, even if a portion of the payment is for the perpetual care of the entirety of the cemetery.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Bequests or gifts to a 501(c)(13) cemetery are not deductible for federal estate tax purposes or gift tax purposes.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] Historically, cemeteries were exempt from local property taxes and excise taxes in most states because states generally considered cemeteries to be performing a recognized civic service.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] The Tariff Act of 1913 provided an exemption from federal income taxes for mutual cemetery companies that were organized and operated exclusively "for the benefit of their members".
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] In 1921, Congress extended the tax-exemption to cemetery companies that are not mutual and to cemetery companies that are not operated for profit as well as any corporation solely incorporated to operate a cemetery and whose net gains do not inure to any person.
[src:american-physical-society/501-c-organization] In 1970, Congress added crematorium in the definition of cemetery for the purposes of Section 501(c)(13).
[src:american-physical-society/abraham-pais-prize] The **Abraham Pais Prize for History of Physics** is an award given each year since 2005 jointly by the American Physical Society and the American Institute of Physics for "*outstanding scholarly achievements in the history of physics*".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Albert Abraham Michelson was born on December 19, 1852, in Strelno (now Strzelno, Poland), Prussia, into a Polish-Jewish family.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] He moved to the United States with his parents in 1855, at the age of 2.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] He grew up in the mining towns of Murphy's Camp, California, and Virginia City, Nevada, where his father was a merchant.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] His family was non-religious, and Michelson himself was a lifelong agnostic.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] He spent his high school years in San Francisco in the home of his aunt, Henriette Levy (née Michelson), who was the mother of author Harriet Lane Levy.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] His sister was the novelist Miriam Michelson.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Grant awarded Michelson a special appointment to the U.S.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] During his four years as a midshipman at the Academy, he excelled in optics, heat, climatology and technical drawing.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] After graduating in 1873 and two years at sea, he returned to the Naval Academy in 1875 to become an instructor in physics and chemistry until 1879, when he was posted to the Nautical Almanac Office, Washington (part of the United States Naval Observatory) to work with Simon Newcomb.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] The following year, he took a leave of absence to continue his studies in Europe; he visited the universities of Berlin and Heidelberg in Germany, and the Collège de France and École polytechnique in Paris, France.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated with the sciences, in particular the problem of measuring the speed of light.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] While in Annapolis, he conducted his first experiments on the speed of light as part of a class demonstration in 1877.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] His Annapolis experiment was refined, and in 1879, he measured the speed of light in air to be 299864±51 kilometres per second, and estimated the speed of light in vacuum as 299940 km/s, or 186380 mi/s.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] After two years of studies in Europe, he resigned from the Navy in 1881.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] In 1883, he was appointed Professor of Physics at the Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio, and concentrated on developing an improved interferometer.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he and Edward Morley carried out the famous Michelson–Morley experiment, which failed to detect evidence of the existence of the luminiferous ether.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] He later moved on to use astronomical interferometers in the measurement of stellar diameters and in measuring the separations of binary stars.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] In 1890, Michelson became a professor at Clark University in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] In 1892, he was appointed Professor and the first head of the Department of Physics at the newly-organized University of Chicago, where he remained until his retirement in 1929.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Michelson returned to military service in the closing months of World War I as a Lieutenant Commander in the Naval Reserve, serving in the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] He was promoted to Commander in the reserve in May 1919 and was recalled briefly to active duty in the 9th Naval District before being released from service on September 30, 1921.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died on May 9, 1931, in Pasadena, California, at the age of 78.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated by light all his life.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Once asked why he studied light, he reputedly said, "because it's so much fun".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] As early as 1869, while serving as an officer in the United States Navy, Michelson started planning a repeat of the rotating-mirror method of Léon Foucault for measuring the speed of light, using improved optics and a longer baseline.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] He conducted some preliminary measurements using largely improvised equipment in 1878, about the same time that his work came to the attention of Simon Newcomb, director of the Nautical Almanac Office who was already advanced in planning his own study.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's formal experiments took place in June and July 1879.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] He constructed a frame building along the north sea wall of the Naval Academy to house the machinery.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Michelson published his result of 299,910 ± 50 km/s in 1879 before joining Newcomb in Washington DC to assist with his measurements there.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Thus began a long professional collaboration and friendship between the two.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Simon Newcomb, with his more adequately funded project, obtained a value of 299,860 ± 30 km/s, just at the extreme edge of consistency with Michelson's.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Michelson continued to "refine" his method and in 1883 published a measurement of 299,853 ± 60 km/s, rather closer to that of his mentor.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] In 1906, a novel electrical method was used by E.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Rosa and the National Bureau of Standards to obtain a value for the speed of light of 299,781 ± 10 km/s.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Though this result has subsequently been shown to be severely biased by the poor electrical standards in use at the time, it seems to have set a fashion for rather lower measured values.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] From 1920, Michelson started planning a definitive measurement from the Mount Wilson Observatory, using a baseline to Lookout Mountain, a prominent bump on the south ridge of Mount San Antonio ("Old Baldy"), some 22 miles distant.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] In 1922, the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey began two years of painstaking measurement of the baseline using the recently available invar tapes.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] With the baseline length established in 1924, measurements were carried out over the next two years to obtain the published value of 299,796 ± 4 km/s.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Famous as the measurement is, it was beset by problems, not least of which was the haze created by the smoke from forest fires which blurred the mirror image.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] The now-famous Michelson–Morley experiment also influenced the affirmation attempts of peer Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and special relativity, using similar optical instrumentation.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] These instruments and related collaborations included the participation of fellow physicists Dayton Miller, Hendrik Lorentz, and Robert Shankland.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] The period after 1927 marked the advent of new measurements of the speed of light using novel electro-optic devices, all substantially lower than Michelson's 1926 value.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Michelson sought another measurement, but this time in an evacuated tube to avoid difficulties in interpreting the image owing to atmospheric effects.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] In 1929, he began a collaboration with Francis G.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Pease and Fred Pearson to perform a measurement in a 1.6 km tube 3 feet in diameter at the Irvine Ranch near Santa Ana, California.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] In multiple reflections the light path was increased to 5 miles.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] For the first time in history the speed of light was measured in an almost perfect vacuum of 0.5 mm of mercury.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died with only 36 of the 233 measurement series completed and the experiment was subsequently beset by geological instability and condensation problems before the result of 299774±11 km/s, consistent with the prevailing electro-optic values, was published posthumously in 1935.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] During June and early July 1879, Michelson refined experimental arrangements from those developed by Hippolyte Fizeau and Léon Foucault.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] For instance, he adopted a steel measuring tape with a said length of 100 feet and he intended to measure tens of times across the distance; still, he measured its length against a copy of the official standard yard to find out it as 100.006 feet, thus eliminating a systematic error, albeit small.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Aside from the efforts to reduce as much as possible the systematic errors, repeated measurements were performed at multiple levels to obtain more accurate results.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] To realize that, he also strived to have each measurement not influencing each other, thus being mutually independent random variables.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] A statistical model for repeated measurements with the assumption of independence or identical distributions is unrealistic.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] In the case of light speed study, each measurement is approached as the sum of quantity of interest and measurement error.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] The law of large numbers suggests to estimate the expectation by the sample mean.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he collaborated with colleague Edward Williams Morley of Western Reserve University, now part of Case Western Reserve University, in the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Their experiment for the expected motion of the Earth relative to the aether, the hypothetical medium in which light was supposed to travel, resulted in a null result.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Surprised, Michelson repeated the experiment with greater and greater precision over the next years, but continued to find no ability to measure the aether.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] The Michelson–Morley results were immensely influential in the physics community, leading Hendrik Lorentz to devise his now-famous Lorentz contraction equations as a means of explaining the null result.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] There has been some historical controversy over whether Albert Einstein was aware of the Michelson–Morley results when he developed his theory of special relativity, which pronounced the aether to be "superfluous".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] In a later interview, Einstein said of the Michelson–Morley experiment, "I was not conscious it had influenced me directly ...
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] I guess I just took it for granted that it was true." Regardless of Einstein's specific knowledge, the experiment is today considered the canonical experiment in regards to showing the lack of a detectable aether.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] The precision of their equipment allowed Michelson and Morley to be the first to get precise values for the fine structure in the atomic spectral lines for which in 1916 Arnold Sommerfeld gave a theoretical explanation, introducing the fine-structure constant.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Pease made the first measurement of the diameter of a star other than the Sun.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Michelson had invented astronomical interferometry and built such an instrument at the Mount Wilson Observatory which was used to measure the diameter of the red giant Betelgeuse.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] A periscope arrangement was used to direct light from two subpupils, separated by up to 20 feet (6m), into the main pupil of the 100 inch (2.5m) Hooker Telescope, producing interference fringes observed through the eyepiece.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] The measurement of stellar diameters and the separations of binary stars took up an increasing amount of Michelson's life after this.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Beginning in the 1970s, astronomical interferometry was revived, with the configurations using two (or more) separate apertures (with diameters small compared to their separation) being often referred to as "Michelson Stellar Interferometry".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] This was to distinguish it from speckle interferometry, but should not be confused with the Michelson interferometer which is one common *laboratory* interferometer configuration of which the interferometer used in the Michelson–Morley experiment was an instance.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's concept of interfering light from two relatively small apertures separated by a substantial distance (but with that distance, or *baseline*, now often as long as hundreds of meters) is employed at modern operational observatories such as VLTI, CHARA and the U.S.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Gravitational waves are detected using a Michelson interferometer with a laser light source.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] In 2020 there were three Michelson interferometer gravitational wave detectors operational, and a fourth under construction.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] These Michelson interferometers have arms 4 kilometers in length, set at 90 degree angles to each other, with the light passing through 1 m diameter vacuum tubes running their entire length.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] A passing gravitational wave will slightly stretch one arm as it shortens the other.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] This is precisely the motion to which these Michelson interferometers are most sensitive.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] As of 2020 fifteen gravitational wave events had been observed using these Michelson interferometers.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] In the 1890s Michelson built a mechanical device called the harmonic analyzer, for computing coefficients of Fourier series and drawing graphs of their partial sums.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Stratton published a paper about this machine in the *American Journal of Science* in 1898.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] In 1877, Michelson married Margaret Hemingway, daughter of a wealthy New York stockbroker and lawyer and the niece of his commander William T.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] In 1899, Michelson married Edna Stanton.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] He is a great uncle of physicist Peter Michelson.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] In Season 3 Episode 26 of the television series *Bonanza* ("Look to the Stars", broadcast March 18, 1962), Ben Cartwright (Lorne Greene) helps the 16-year-old Michelson (portrayed by 25-year-old Douglas Lambert (1936–1986)) obtain an appointment to the U.S.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Naval Academy, despite the opposition of the bigoted town schoolteacher (played by William Schallert).
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] *Bonanza* was set in and around Virginia City, Nevada, where Michelson lived with his parents prior to leaving for the Naval Academy.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] In a voice-over at the end of the episode, Greene mentions Michelson's 1907 Nobel Prize.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] The home in which Michelson lived as a child in Murphys Camp, California, was in the store of his father, first on Main Street, across from the Sperry & Perry Hotel, and after the 1859 fire in a store next to the hotel.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] His aunt Bertha Meyers owned a house on Main Street toward the east end of town and Michelson probably visited her family there frequently.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] New Beast Theater Works in collaboration with High Concept Laboratories produced a 'semi-opera' about Michelson, his obsessive working style and its effect on his family life.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] The production ran from February 11 to 26, 2011, in Chicago at The Building Stage.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was portrayed by Jon Stutzman.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] The play was directed by David Maral with music composed by Joshua Dumas.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Norman Fitzroy Maclean wrote an essay "Billiards Is a Good Game"; published in *The Norman Maclean Reader* (ed.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Alan Weltzien, 2008), it is an appreciation of Michelson from Maclean's vantage point as a graduate student regularly watching him play billiards.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] The University of Chicago Residence Halls remembered Michelson and his achievements by dedicating 'Michelson House' in his honor.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Case Western Reserve has dedicated a Michelson House to him, and Michelson Hall (an academic building of science classrooms, laboratories and offices) at the United States Naval Academy also bears his name.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Laboratory at Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake in Ridgecrest, California, is named for him.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] There is a display in the publicly accessible area of the Lab which includes facsimiles of Michelson's Nobel Prize medal, the prize document, and examples of his diffraction gratings.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] In 2017, a newly renovated physics research center at the University of Chicago was renamed in honor of Michelson as well.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Numerous awards, lectures, and honors have been created in Albert A.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award presented every year by the Computer Measurement Group; the Albert A.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award given by the Navy League of the United States; and the Michelson Memorial Lecture Series presented annually by the Division of Mathematics and Science at the U.S.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-a-michelson] The Computer Measurement Group gives the annual A.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] Born as a subject to the Kingdom of Württemberg, part of the German Empire, Einstein moved to Switzerland in 1895, forsaking his citizenship the following year.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] In 1896, at the age of seventeen, he enrolled in the mathematics and physics teaching diploma program at the Swiss federal polytechnic school in Zurich, graduating in 1900.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] He acquired Swiss citizenship a year later, which he kept for the rest of his life, and afterwards secured a permanent position at the Swiss Patent Office in Bern.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] In 1905, he submitted a successful PhD dissertation to the University of Zurich.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] In 1914, he moved to Berlin to join the Prussian Academy of Sciences and the Humboldt University of Berlin, becoming director of the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute for Physics in 1917; he also became a Prussian and consequently also German citizen again.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] In 1933, while Einstein was visiting the United States, Adolf Hitler came to power in Germany.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] Horrified by the Nazi persecution of his fellow Jews, he decided to remain in the US, and was granted American citizenship in 1940.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] On the eve of World War II, he endorsed a letter to President Franklin D.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] Roosevelt alerting him to the potential German nuclear weapons program and recommending that the US begin similar research, later carried out as the Manhattan Project.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] In 1905, sometimes described as his *annus mirabilis* (miracle year), he published four groundbreaking papers.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] In them, he outlined a theory of the photoelectric effect, explained Brownian motion, introduced his special theory of relativity, and demonstrated that if the special theory is correct, mass and energy are equivalent to each other.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] In 1915, he proposed a general theory of relativity that extended his system of mechanics to incorporate gravitation.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] A paper that he published the following year laid out the implications of general relativity for the modeling of the structure and evolution of the universe as a whole.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] It introduced the cosmological constant and is further regarded as the first step in the field of modern theoretical cosmology.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] In the middle part of his career, Einstein made important contributions to statistical mechanics and quantum theory.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] Especially notable was his work on the quantum physics of radiation, in which light consists of particles, subsequently called photons.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] With physicist Satyendra Nath Bose, he laid the groundwork for Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] For much of the last phase of his academic life, Einstein worked on two endeavors that ultimately proved unsuccessful.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] First, he advocated against quantum theory's introduction of fundamental randomness into science's picture of the world, objecting that "God does not play dice".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] Second, he attempted to devise a unified field theory by generalizing his geometric theory of gravitation to include electromagnetism.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] As a result, he became increasingly isolated from mainstream modern physics.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] Many things are named after him, including the element Einsteinium.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p01] In 1999, he was named *Time*'s Person of the Century.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein was born in Ulm as a subject to the Kingdom of Württemberg in the German Empire on 14 March 1879.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] His parents, secular Ashkenazi Jews, were Hermann Einstein, a salesman and engineer, and Pauline Koch.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In 1880, the family moved to Munich's borough of Ludwigsvorstadt-Isarvorstadt, where Einstein's father and his uncle Jakob founded Elektrotechnische Fabrik J.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein & Cie, a company that manufactured electrical equipment based on direct current.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] When he was very young, his parents worried that he had a learning disability because he was very slow to learn to talk.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] When he was five and sick in bed, his father brought him a compass.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] This sparked his lifelong fascination with electromagnetism.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Peter's Catholic elementary school in Munich from the age of five.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] When he was eight, he was transferred to the Luitpold Gymnasium, where he received advanced primary and then secondary school education.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In 1894, Hermann and Jakob's company tendered for a contract to install electric lighting in Munich, but without success—they lacked the capital that would have been required to update their technology from direct current to the more efficient, alternating current alternative.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] The failure of their bid forced them to sell their Munich factory and search for new opportunities elsewhere.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] The Einstein family moved to Italy, first to Milan and a few months later to Pavia, where they settled in Palazzo Cornazzani.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein, then fifteen, stayed behind in Munich in order to finish his schooling.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] His father wanted him to study electrical engineering, but he was a fractious pupil who found the Gymnasium's regimen and teaching methods far from congenial.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He later wrote that the school's policy of strict rote learning was harmful to creativity.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] At the end of December 1894, a letter from a doctor persuaded the Luitpold's authorities to release him from its care, and he joined his family in Pavia.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] While in Italy as a teenager, he wrote an essay titled "On the Investigation of the State of the Ether in a Magnetic Field".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein excelled at physics and mathematics from an early age, and soon acquired the mathematical expertise normally only found in a child several years his senior.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He began teaching himself algebra, calculus and Euclidean geometry when he was twelve; he made such rapid progress that he discovered an original proof of the Pythagorean theorem before his thirteenth birthday.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] A family tutor, Max Talmud, said that only a short time after he had given the twelve year old Einstein a geometry textbook, the boy "had worked through the whole book.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He thereupon devoted himself to higher mathematics ...
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Soon the flight of his mathematical genius was so high I could not follow." Einstein recorded that he had "mastered integral and differential calculus" while still just fourteen.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] His love of algebra and geometry was so great that at twelve, he was already confident that nature could be understood as a "mathematical structure".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] At thirteen, when his range of enthusiasms had broadened to include music and philosophy, Talmud introduced Einstein to Kant's *Critique of Pure Reason*.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In 1895, at the age of sixteen, Einstein sat the entrance examination for the federal polytechnic school (later the Eidgenössische Technische Hochschule, ETH) in Zurich, Switzerland.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He failed to reach the required standard in the general part of the test, but performed with distinction in physics and mathematics.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] On the advice of the polytechnic's principal, he completed his secondary education at the Argovian cantonal school (a gymnasium) in Aarau, Switzerland, graduating in 1896.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] While lodging in Aarau with the family of Jost Winteler, he fell in love with Winteler's daughter, Marie.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In January 1896, with his father's approval, Einstein renounced his citizenship of the German Kingdom of Württemberg in order to avoid conscription into military service.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] The *Matura* (graduation for the successful completion of higher secondary schooling), awarded to him in September 1896, acknowledged him to have performed well across most of the curriculum, allotting him a top grade of 6 for history, physics, algebra, geometry, and descriptive geometry.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] At seventeen, he enrolled in the four-year mathematics and physics teaching diploma program at the federal polytechnic school.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He befriended fellow student Marcel Grossmann, who would help him there to get by despite his loose study habits, and later to mathematically underpin his revolutionary insights into physics.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Marie Winteler, a year older than him, took up a teaching post in Olsberg, Switzerland.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] The five other polytechnic school freshmen following the same course as Einstein included just one woman, a twenty year old Serbian, Mileva Marić.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Over the next few years, the pair spent many hours discussing their shared interests and learning about topics in physics that the polytechnic school's lectures did not cover.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In his letters to Marić, Einstein confessed that exploring science with her by his side was much more enjoyable than reading a textbook in solitude.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Eventually the two students became not only friends, but also lovers.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Historians of physics are divided on the question of the extent to which Marić contributed to the insights of Einstein's *annus mirabilis* publications.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] There is at least some evidence that he was influenced by her scientific ideas, but there are scholars who doubt whether her impact on his thought was of any great significance at all.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Correspondence between Einstein and Marić, discovered and published in 1987, revealed that the couple had a daughter named Lieserl.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] She was born in early 1902 while Marić was visiting her parents in Novi Sad.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] When Marić returned to Switzerland the child was no longer with her.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In a letter written in September 1903, Einstein suggested that the girl was either given up for adoption or died of scarlet fever in infancy.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein and Marić married in January 1903.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In May 1904, their son Hans Albert was born in Bern, Switzerland.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Their son Eduard was born in Zurich in July 1910.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In 1912, Einstein entered into a relationship with Elsa Löwenthal, who was both his first cousin on his mother's side and his second cousin on his father's.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] When Marić learned of his infidelity soon after moving to Berlin with him in April 1914, she returned to Zurich, taking Hans Albert and Eduard with her.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein and Marić were granted a divorce on 14 February 1919 on the grounds of having lived apart for five years.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] As part of the divorce settlement, Einstein agreed that if he were to win a Nobel Prize, he would give the money that he received to Marić; he won the prize two years later.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In 1923, he began a relationship with a secretary named Betty Neumann, the niece of his close friend Hans Mühsam.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Löwenthal nevertheless remained loyal to him, accompanying him when he emigrated to the United States in 1933.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In 1935, she was diagnosed with heart and kidney problems.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] A volume of Einstein's letters released by the Hebrew University of Jerusalem in 2006 added some other women with whom he was romantically involved.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] They included Margarete Lebach (a married Austrian), Estella Katzenellenbogen (the rich owner of a florist business), Toni Mendel (a wealthy Jewish widow) and Ethel Michanowski (a Berlin socialite), with whom he spent time and from whom he accepted gifts while married to Löwenthal.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] After being widowed, Einstein was briefly in a relationship with Margarita Konenkova, thought by some to be a Russian spy; her husband, the Russian sculptor Sergei Konenkov, created the bronze bust of Einstein at the Institute for Advanced Study at Princeton.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Following an episode of acute mental illness at about the age of twenty, Einstein's son Eduard was diagnosed with schizophrenia.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He spent the remainder of his life either in the care of his mother or in temporary confinement in an asylum.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] After her death, he was committed permanently to Burghölzli, the Psychiatric University Hospital in Zurich.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein graduated from the federal polytechnic school in 1900, duly certified as competent to teach mathematics and physics.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] His successful acquisition of Swiss citizenship in February 1901 was not followed by the usual sequel of conscription; the Swiss authorities deemed him medically unfit for military service.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He found that Swiss schools too appeared to have no use for him, failing to offer him a teaching position despite the almost two years that he spent applying for one.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Eventually it was with the help of Marcel Grossmann's father that he secured a post in Bern at the Swiss Patent Office, as an assistant examiner – level III.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Patent applications that landed on Einstein's desk for his evaluation included ideas for a gravel sorter and an electric typewriter.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] His employers were pleased enough with his work to make his position permanent in 1903, although they did not think that he should be promoted until he had "fully mastered machine technology".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] It is conceivable that his labors at the patent office had a bearing on his development of his special theory of relativity.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He arrived at his revolutionary ideas about space, time and light through thought experiments about the transmission of signals and the synchronization of clocks, matters which also figured in some of the inventions submitted to him for assessment.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In 1902, Einstein and his friends Conrad Habicht and Maurice Solovine, whom he had met in Bern, formed a group that held regular meetings to discuss science and philosophy.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Their choice of a name for their club, the Olympia Academy, was an ironic comment upon its far from Olympian status.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Sometimes they were joined by Marić, who limited her participation in their proceedings to careful listening.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] The thinkers whose works they reflected upon included Henri Poincaré, Ernst Mach and David Hume, all of whom significantly influenced Einstein's own subsequent ideas and beliefs.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's first paper, "Folgerungen aus den Capillaritätserscheinungen" ("Conclusions drawn from the phenomena of capillarity"), in which he proposed a model of intermolecular attraction that he afterwards disavowed as worthless, was published in the journal *Annalen der Physik* in 1901.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] His 24-page doctoral dissertation also addressed a topic in molecular physics.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Titled "Eine neue Bestimmung der Moleküldimensionen" ("A New Determination of Molecular Dimensions") and dedicated "Meinem Freunde Herr Dr.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Marcel Grossmann gewidmet" (to his friend Marcel Grossman), it was completed on 30 April 1905 and approved by Professor Alfred Kleiner of the University of Zurich three months later.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] The publications deeply impressed Einstein's contemporaries.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's sabbatical as a civil servant approached its end in 1908, when he secured a junior teaching position at the University of Bern.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In 1909, a lecture on relativistic electrodynamics that he gave at the University of Zurich, much admired by Alfred Kleiner, led to Zurich's luring him away from Bern with a newly created associate professorship.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Promotion to a full professorship followed in April 1911, when he took up a chair at the German Charles-Ferdinand University in Prague, a move which required him to become an Austrian citizen of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, which was not completed.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] His time in Prague saw him producing eleven research papers.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] From 30 October to 3 November 1911, Einstein attended the first Solvay Conference on Physics.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In July 1912, he returned to his *alma mater*, the ETH Zurich, to take up a chair in theoretical physics.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] His teaching activities there centered on thermodynamics and analytical mechanics, and his research interests included the molecular theory of heat, continuum mechanics and the development of a relativistic theory of gravitation.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In his work on the latter topic, he was assisted by his friend Marcel Grossmann, whose knowledge of the kind of mathematics required was greater than his own.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In the spring of 1913, two German visitors, Max Planck and Walther Nernst, called upon Einstein in Zurich in the hope of persuading him to relocate to Berlin.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Their invitation was all the more appealing to him because Berlin happened to be the home of his latest girlfriend, Elsa Löwenthal.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He duly joined the Academy on 24 July 1913, and moved into an apartment in the Berlin district of Dahlem on 1 April 1914.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He was installed in his Humboldt University position shortly thereafter.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] The outbreak of the First World War in July 1914 marked the beginning of Einstein's gradual estrangement from the nation of his birth.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] However, this expression of his doubts about German policy did not prevent him from being elected to a two-year term as president of the German Physical Society in 1916.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] When the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute for Physics opened its doors the following year—its foundation delayed because of the war—Einstein was appointed its first director, just as Planck and Nernst had promised.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein was elected a Foreign Member of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1920, and a Foreign Member of the Royal Society in 1921.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In 1922, he was awarded the 1921 Nobel Prize in Physics "for his services to Theoretical Physics, and especially for his discovery of the law of the photoelectric effect".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Bose derived the Planck spectrum in 1924.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] That same year, Einstein was elected an International Honorary Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Britain's closest equivalent of the Nobel award, the Royal Society's Copley Medal, was not hung around Einstein's neck until 1925.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He was elected an International Member of the American Philosophical Society in 1930.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein resigned from the Prussian Academy in March 1933.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] His accomplishments in Berlin had included the completion of the general theory of relativity, proving the Einstein–de Haas effect, contributing to the quantum theory of radiation, and the development of Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In 1911, he first calculated the gravitational deflection of light passing close to the Sun, a prediction later adjusted upon completion of the general theory of relativity.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He reworked his calculation in 1913, having now found a way to model gravitation with the Riemann curvature tensor of a non-Euclidean four-dimensional spacetime.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] A total eclipse of the Sun that took place on 29 May 1919 provided an opportunity to put his theory of gravitational lensing to the test, and observations performed by Sir Arthur Eddington yielded results that were consistent with his calculations.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Eddington's work was reported at length in newspapers around the world.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] On 7 November 1919, for example, the leading British newspaper, *The Times*, printed a banner headline that read: "Revolution in Science – New Theory of the Universe – Newtonian Ideas Overthrown".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein began his new life as an intellectual icon in America, where he arrived on 2 April 1921.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He was welcomed to New York City by Mayor John Francis Hylan, and then spent three weeks giving lectures and attending receptions.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He spoke several times at Columbia University and Princeton, and in Washington, he visited the White House with representatives of the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He returned to Europe via London, where he was the guest of the philosopher and statesman Viscount Haldane.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He used his time in the British capital to meet several people prominent in British scientific, political or intellectual life, and to deliver a lecture at King's College.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In July 1921, he published an essay, "My First Impression of the U.S.A.", in which he sought to sketch the American character.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He wrote of his transatlantic hosts in highly approving terms: "What strikes a visitor is the joyous, positive attitude to life ...
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In 1922, Einstein's travels were to the old world rather than the new.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He devoted six months to a tour of Asia that saw him speaking in Japan, Singapore and Sri Lanka (then known as Ceylon).
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] After his first public lecture in Tokyo, he met Emperor Yoshihito and his wife at the Imperial Palace, with thousands of spectators thronging the streets in the hope of catching a glimpse of him.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] (In a letter to his sons, he wrote that Japanese people seemed to him to be generally modest, intelligent and considerate, and to have a true appreciation of art.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] But his picture of them in his diary was less flattering: "[the] intellectual needs of this nation seem to be weaker than their artistic ones – natural disposition?" His journal also contains views of China and India which were uncomplimentary.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Of Chinese people, he wrote that "even the children are spiritless and look obtuse...
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] It would be a pity if these Chinese supplant all other races.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] For the likes of us the mere thought is unspeakably dreary".) He was greeted with even greater enthusiasm on the last leg of his tour, in which he spent twelve days in Mandatory Palestine, newly entrusted to British rule by the League of Nations in the aftermath of the First World War.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Sir Herbert Samuel, the British High Commissioner, welcomed him with a degree of ceremony normally only accorded to a visiting head of state, including a cannon salute.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] One reception held in his honor was stormed by people determined to hear him speak: he told them that he was happy that Jews were beginning to be recognized as a force in the world.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] On April 6, 1922, during a visit to Paris, Einstein engaged in a debate on relativity with the philosopher Henri Bergson.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] This dispute has had widespread ramifications for the humanities and was an academic *cause célèbre* at the time.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's decision to tour the eastern hemisphere in 1922 meant that he was unable to go to Stockholm in the December of that year to participate in the Nobel prize ceremony.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] His place at the traditional Nobel banquet was taken by a German diplomat, who gave a speech praising him not only as a physicist but also as a campaigner for peace.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] A two-week visit to Spain that he undertook in 1923 saw him collecting another award, a membership of the Spanish Academy of Sciences signified by a diploma handed to him by King Alfonso XIII.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] He was appointed as a German delegate rather than as a representative of Switzerland because of the machinations of two Catholic activists, Oskar Halecki and Giuseppe Motta.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] By persuading Secretary General Eric Drummond to deny Einstein the place on the committee reserved for a Swiss thinker, they created an opening for Gonzague de Reynold, who used his League of Nations position as a platform from which to promote traditional Catholic doctrine.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's former physics professor Hendrik Lorentz and the Polish chemist Marie Curie were also members of the committee.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In March and April 1925, Einstein and his wife visited South America, where they spent about a week in Brazil, a week in Uruguay and a month in Argentina.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] In December 1930, Einstein began another significant sojourn in the United States, drawn back to the US by the offer of a two month research fellowship at the California Institute of Technology.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Caltech supported him in his wish that he should not be exposed to quite as much attention from the media as he had experienced when visiting the US in 1921, and he therefore declined all the invitations to receive prizes or make speeches that his admirers poured down upon him.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] But he remained willing to allow his fans at least some of the time with him that they requested.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] After arriving in New York City, Einstein was taken to various places and events, including Chinatown, a lunch with the editors of *The New York Times*, and a performance of *Carmen* at the Metropolitan Opera, where he was cheered by the audience on his arrival.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] During the days following, he was given the keys to the city by Mayor Jimmy Walker and met Nicholas Murray Butler, the president of Columbia University, who described Einstein as "the ruling monarch of the mind".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Harry Emerson Fosdick, pastor at New York's Riverside Church, gave Einstein a tour of the church and showed him a full-size statue that the church made of Einstein, standing at the entrance.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Also during his stay in New York, he joined a crowd of 15,000 people at Madison Square Garden during a Hanukkah celebration.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein next traveled to California, where he met Caltech president and Nobel laureate Robert A.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] His friendship with Millikan was "awkward", as Millikan "had a penchant for patriotic militarism", where Einstein was a pronounced pacifist.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] During an address to Caltech's students, Einstein noted that science was often inclined to do more harm than good.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] This aversion to war also led Einstein to befriend author Upton Sinclair and film star Charlie Chaplin, both noted for their pacifism.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Carl Laemmle, head of Universal Studios, gave Einstein a tour of his studio and introduced him to Chaplin.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] They had an instant rapport, with Chaplin inviting Einstein and his wife, Elsa, to his home for dinner.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p02] Chaplin said Einstein's outward persona, calm and gentle, seemed to conceal a "highly emotional temperament", from which came his "extraordinary intellectual energy".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Chaplin's film *City Lights* was to premiere a few days later in Hollywood, and Chaplin invited Einstein and Elsa to join him as his special guests.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Walter Isaacson, Einstein's biographer, described this as "one of the most memorable scenes in the new era of celebrity".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Chaplin visited Einstein at his home on a later trip to Berlin and recalled his "modest little flat" and the piano at which he had begun writing his theory.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Chaplin speculated that it was "possibly used as kindling wood by the Nazis".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein and Chaplin were cheered at the premiere of the film.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] In February 1933, while on a visit to the United States, Einstein knew he could not return to Germany with the rise to power of the Nazis under Germany's new chancellor, Adolf Hitler.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] While at American universities in early 1933, he undertook his third two-month visiting professorship at the California Institute of Technology in Pasadena.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] In February and March 1933, the Gestapo repeatedly raided his family's apartment in Berlin.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He and his wife Elsa returned to Europe in March, and during the trip, they learned that the German Reichstag had passed the Enabling Act on 23 March, transforming Hitler's government into a *de facto* legal dictatorship, and that they would not be able to proceed to Berlin.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Later on, they heard that their cottage had been raided by the Nazis and Einstein's personal sailboat confiscated.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Upon landing in Antwerp, Belgium on 28 March, Einstein immediately went to the German consulate and surrendered his passport, formally renouncing his German citizenship.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] The renunciation was at first refused, but the Nazi government finally revoked his citizenship on 24 March 1934.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] The Nazis later sold his boat and converted his cottage into a Hitler Youth camp.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] In April 1933, Einstein discovered that the new German government had passed laws barring Jews from holding any official positions, including teaching at universities.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Historian Gerald Holton describes how, with "virtually no audible protest being raised by their colleagues", thousands of Jewish scientists were suddenly forced to give up their university positions and their names were removed from the rolls of institutions where they were employed.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] In a subsequent letter to physicist and friend Max Born, who had already emigrated from Germany to England, Einstein wrote, "...
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was now without a permanent home, unsure where he would live and work, and equally worried about the fate of countless other scientists still in Germany.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Aided by the Academic Assistance Council, founded in April 1933 by British Liberal politician William Beveridge to help academics escape Nazi persecution, Einstein was able to leave Germany.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He rented a house in De Haan, Belgium, where he lived for a few months.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] In late July 1933, he visited England for about six weeks at the invitation of the British Member of Parliament Commander Oliver Locker-Lampson, who had become friends with him in the preceding years.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Locker-Lampson invited him to stay near his Cromer home in a secluded wooden cabin on Roughton Heath in the Parish of Roughton, Norfolk.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] To protect Einstein, Locker-Lampson had two bodyguards watch over him; a photo of them carrying shotguns and guarding Einstein was published in the *Daily Herald* on 24 July 1933.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Locker-Lampson took Einstein to meet Winston Churchill at his home, and later, Austen Chamberlain and former Prime Minister Lloyd George.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein asked them to help bring Jewish scientists out of Germany.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] British historian Martin Gilbert notes that Churchill responded immediately, and sent his friend physicist Frederick Lindemann to Germany to seek out Jewish scientists and place them in British universities.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Churchill later observed that as a result of Germany having driven the Jews out, they had lowered their "technical standards" and put the Allies' technology ahead of theirs.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein later contacted leaders of other nations, including Turkey's Prime Minister, İsmet İnönü, to whom he wrote in September 1933, requesting placement of unemployed German-Jewish scientists.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] As a result of Einstein's letter, Jewish invitees to Turkey eventually totaled over "1,000 saved individuals".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Locker-Lampson also submitted a bill to parliament to extend British citizenship to Einstein, during which period Einstein made a number of public appearances describing the crisis brewing in Europe.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] In one of his speeches he denounced Germany's treatment of Jews, while at the same time he introduced a bill promoting Jewish citizenship in Palestine, as they were being denied citizenship elsewhere.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] In his speech he described Einstein as a "citizen of the world" who should be offered a temporary shelter in the UK.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Both bills failed, however, and Einstein then accepted an earlier offer from the Institute for Advanced Study, in Princeton, New Jersey, US, to become a resident scholar.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] On 3 October 1933, Einstein delivered a speech on the importance of academic freedom before a packed audience at the Royal Albert Hall in London, with *The Times* reporting he was wildly cheered throughout.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Four days later he returned to the US and took up a position at the Institute for Advanced Study, noted for having become a refuge for scientists fleeing Nazi Germany.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] At the time, most American universities, including Harvard, Princeton and Yale, had minimal or no Jewish faculty or students, as a result of their Jewish quotas, which lasted until the late 1940s.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was still undecided about his future.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein's affiliation with the Institute for Advanced Study would last until his death in 1955.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He was one of the four first selected (along with John von Neumann, Kurt Gödel and Hermann Weyl) at the new Institute.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He soon developed a close friendship with Gödel; the two would take long walks together discussing their work.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Bruria Kaufman, his assistant, later became a physicist.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] During this period, Einstein tried to develop a unified field theory and to refute the accepted interpretation of quantum physics, both unsuccessfully.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He lived in Princeton at his home from 1935 onwards.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] The Albert Einstein House was made a National Historic Landmark in 1976.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] In 1939, a group of Hungarian scientists that included émigré physicist Leó Szilárd attempted to alert Washington, D.C. to ongoing Nazi atomic bomb research.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He was asked to lend his support by writing a letter, with Szilárd, to President Franklin D.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Roosevelt, recommending the US pay attention and engage in its own nuclear weapons research.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] The letter is believed to be "arguably the key stimulus for the U.S. adoption of serious investigations into nuclear weapons on the eve of the U.S. entry into World War II".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] In addition to the letter, Einstein used his connections with the Belgian royal family and the Belgian queen mother to get access with a personal envoy to the White House's Oval Office.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Some say that as a result of Einstein's letter and his meetings with Roosevelt, the US entered the "race" to develop the bomb, drawing on its "immense material, financial, and scientific resources" to initiate the Manhattan Project.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] For Einstein, "war was a disease ... [and] he called for resistance to war." By signing the letter to Roosevelt, some argue he went against his pacifist principles.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein became an American citizen in 1940.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Not long after settling into his career at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey, he expressed his appreciation of the meritocracy in American culture compared to Europe.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He recognized the "right of individuals to say and think what they pleased" without social barriers.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] As a result, individuals were encouraged, he said, to be more creative, a trait he valued from his early education.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein joined the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) in Princeton, where he campaigned for the civil rights of African Americans.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He considered racism America's "worst disease", seeing it as "handed down from one generation to the next".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] As part of his involvement, he corresponded with civil rights activist W.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Du Bois and was prepared to testify on his behalf during his trial as an alleged foreign agent in 1951.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] When Einstein offered to be a character witness for Du Bois, the judge decided to drop the case.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] In 1946, Einstein visited Lincoln University in Pennsylvania, a historically black college, where he was awarded an honorary degree.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Lincoln was the first university in the United States to grant college degrees to African Americans; alumni include Langston Hughes and Thurgood Marshall.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein gave a speech about racism in America, adding, "I do not intend to be quiet about it." A resident of Princeton recalls that Einstein had once paid the college tuition for a black student.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein has said, "Being a Jew myself, perhaps I can understand and empathize with how black people feel as victims of discrimination".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Isaacson writes that "When Marian Anderson, the black contralto, came to Princeton for a concert in 1937, the Nassau Inn refused her a room.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] So Einstein invited her to stay at his house on Main Street, in what was a deeply personal as well as symbolic gesture ...
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] In 1918, Einstein was one of the signatories of the founding proclamation of the German Democratic Party, a liberal party.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Later in his life, Einstein's political view was in favor of socialism and critical of capitalism, which he detailed in his essays such as "Why Socialism?".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] His opinions on the Bolsheviks also changed with time.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] In 1925, he criticized them for not having a "well-regulated system of government" and called their rule a "regime of terror and a tragedy in human history".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein offered and was called on to give judgments and opinions on matters often unrelated to theoretical physics or mathematics.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He strongly advocated the idea of a democratic global government that would check the power of nation-states in the framework of a world federation.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He wrote "I advocate world government because I am convinced that there is no other possible way of eliminating the most terrible danger in which man has ever found himself." The FBI created a secret dossier on Einstein in 1932; by the time of his death, it was 1,427 pages long.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was deeply impressed by Mahatma Gandhi, with whom he corresponded.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He described Gandhi as "a role model for the generations to come".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] The initial connection was established on 27 September 1931, when Wilfrid Israel took his Indian guest V.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Sundaram to his friend Einstein's summer home in the town of Caputh to meet him.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Sundaram was Gandhi's disciple and special envoy, whom Wilfrid Israel met while visiting India and visiting the Indian leader's home in 1925.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] During the visit, Einstein wrote a short letter to Gandhi that was delivered to him through Sundaram, and Gandhi responded quickly with his own letter.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Although in the end Einstein and Gandhi were unable to meet as they had hoped, the direct connection between them was established through Wilfrid Israel.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein, a Jew, was a figurehead leader in the establishment of the Hebrew University of Jerusalem, which opened in 1925.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Earlier, in 1921, he was asked by the biochemist and president of the World Zionist Organization, Chaim Weizmann, to help raise funds for the planned university.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He made suggestions for the creation of an Institute of Agriculture, a Chemical Institute and an Institute of Microbiology in order to fight the various ongoing epidemics such as malaria, which he called an "evil" that was undermining a third of the country's development.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He also promoted the establishment of an Oriental Studies Institute, to include language courses given in both Hebrew and Arabic.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was not a nationalist and opposed the creation of an independent Jewish state.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He felt that the waves of arriving Jews of the Aliyah could live alongside existing Arabs in Palestine.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] The state of Israel was established without his help in 1948; Einstein was limited to a marginal role in the Zionist movement.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Afterward, Einstein adopted a practical attitude, understanding that "there is no going back", and the new state must be supported.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Upon the death of Israeli president Weizmann in November 1952, Prime Minister David Ben-Gurion offered Einstein the largely ceremonial position of President of Israel at the urging of Ezriel Carlebach.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] The offer was presented by Israel's ambassador in Washington, Abba Eban, who explained that the offer "embodies the deepest respect which the Jewish people can repose in any of its sons".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein wrote that he was "deeply moved", but "at once saddened and ashamed" that he could not accept it.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein did not want the office, and the Israeli government did not want him to accept, but felt obliged to make the offer.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Yitzhak Navon, Ben-Gurion's political secretary, and later president, reports Ben-Gurion as saying "Tell me what to do if he says yes!
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] I've had to offer the post to him because it's impossible not to.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Per Lee Smolin, "I believe what allowed Einstein to achieve so much was primarily a moral quality.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He simply cared far more than most of his colleagues that the laws of physics have to explain everything in nature coherently and consistently." Einstein expounded his spiritual outlook in a wide array of writings and interviews.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He said he had sympathy for the impersonal pantheistic God of Baruch Spinoza's philosophy.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He did not believe in a personal god who concerns himself with fates and actions of human beings, a view which he described as naïve.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He clarified, however, that "I am not an atheist", preferring to call himself an agnostic, or a "deeply religious nonbeliever".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He wrote that "A spirit is manifest in the laws of the universe—a spirit vastly superior to that of man, and one in the face of which we with our modest powers must feel humble.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was primarily affiliated with non-religious humanist and Ethical Culture groups in both the UK and US.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He served on the advisory board of the First Humanist Society of New York, and was an honorary associate of the Rationalist Association, which publishes *New Humanist* in Britain.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] For the 75th anniversary of the New York Society for Ethical Culture, he stated that the idea of Ethical Culture embodied his personal conception of what is most valuable and enduring in religious idealism.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein had been sympathetic toward vegetarianism for a long time.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He became a vegetarian himself only during the last part of his life.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] In March 1954 he wrote in a letter: "So I am living without fats, without meat, without fish, but am feeling quite well this way.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein developed an appreciation for music at an early age.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] His mother played the piano reasonably well and wanted her son to learn the violin, not only to instill in him a love of music but also to help him assimilate into German culture.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] According to conductor Leon Botstein, Einstein began playing when he was 5.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] However, he did not enjoy it at that age.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] When he turned 13, he discovered Mozart's violin sonatas, whereupon he became enamored of Mozart's compositions and studied music more willingly.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein taught himself to play without "ever practicing systematically".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He said that "love is a better teacher than a sense of duty".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] At the age of 17, he was heard by a school examiner in Aarau while playing Beethoven's violin sonatas.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] The examiner stated afterward that his playing was "remarkable and revealing of 'great insight'".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] What struck the examiner, writes Botstein, was that Einstein "displayed a deep love of the music, a quality that was and remains in short supply.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Music took on a pivotal and permanent role in Einstein's life from that period on.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Although the idea of becoming a professional musician himself was not on his mind at any time, among those with whom Einstein played chamber music were a few professionals, including Kurt Appelbaum, and he performed for private audiences and friends.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Chamber music had also become a regular part of his social life while living in Bern, Zurich, and Berlin, where he played with Max Planck and his son, among others.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He is sometimes erroneously credited as the editor of the 1937 edition of the Köchel catalog of Mozart's work; that edition was prepared by Alfred Einstein, who may have been a distant relation.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] In 1931, while engaged in research at the California Institute of Technology, he visited the Zoellner family conservatory in Los Angeles, where he played some of Beethoven and Mozart's works with members of the Zoellner Quartet.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Near the end of his life, when the young Juilliard Quartet visited him in Princeton, he played his violin with them, and the quartet was "impressed by Einstein's level of coordination and intonation".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] On 17 April 1955, Einstein experienced internal bleeding caused by the rupture of an abdominal aortic aneurysm, which had previously been reinforced surgically by Rudolph Nissen in 1948.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] He took the draft of a speech he was preparing for a television appearance commemorating the state of Israel's seventh anniversary with him to the hospital, but he did not live to complete it.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein refused surgery, saying, "I want to go when I want.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] It is tasteless to prolong life artificially.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] I will do it elegantly." He died in the Princeton Hospital early the next morning at the age of 76, having continued to work until near the end.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] During the autopsy, the pathologist Thomas Stoltz Harvey removed Einstein's brain for preservation without the permission of his family, in the hope that the neuroscience of the future would be able to discover what made Einstein so intelligent.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein's remains were cremated in Trenton, New Jersey, and his ashes were scattered at an undisclosed location.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] In a memorial lecture delivered on 13 December 1965 at UNESCO headquarters, nuclear physicist J.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Robert Oppenheimer summarized his impression of Einstein as a person: "He was almost wholly without sophistication and wholly without worldliness ...
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein bequeathed his personal archives, library, and intellectual assets to the Hebrew University of Jerusalem in Israel.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Throughout his life, Einstein published hundreds of books and articles.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] He published more than 300 scientific papers and 150 non-scientific ones.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] On 5 December 2014, universities and archives announced the release of Einstein's papers, comprising more than 30,000 unique documents.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In addition to the work he did by himself, he also collaborated with other scientists on additional projects, including the Bose–Einstein statistics, the Einstein refrigerator and others.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's first paper, submitted in 1900 to *Annalen der Physik*, was on capillary attraction.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] It was published in 1901 with the title "Folgerungen aus den Capillaritätserscheinungen", which translates as "Conclusions from the capillarity phenomena".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Two papers he published in 1902–1903 (thermodynamics) attempted to interpret atomic phenomena from a statistical point of view.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] These papers were the foundation for the 1905 paper on Brownian motion, which showed that Brownian movement can be construed as firm evidence that molecules exist.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] His research in 1903 and 1904 was mainly concerned with the effect of finite atomic size on diffusion phenomena.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein returned to the problem of thermodynamic fluctuations, giving a treatment of the density variations in a fluid at its critical point.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Ordinarily, the density fluctuations are controlled by the second derivative of the free energy with respect to the density.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] At the critical point, this derivative is zero, leading to large fluctuations.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] The effect of density fluctuations is that light of all wavelengths is scattered, making the fluid look milky white.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein relates this to Rayleigh scattering, which is what happens when the fluctuation size is much smaller than the wavelength, and which explains why the sky is blue.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein quantitatively derived critical opalescence from a treatment of density fluctuations, and demonstrated how both the effect and Rayleigh scattering originate from the atomistic constitution of matter.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] The *Annus Mirabilis* papers are four articles pertaining to the photoelectric effect (which gave rise to quantum theory), Brownian motion, the special theory of relativity, and *E* = *mc*2 that Einstein published in the *Annalen der Physik* scientific journal in 1905.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] These four works contributed substantially to the foundation of modern physics and changed views on space, time, and matter.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's "*Zur Elektrodynamik bewegter Körper*" ("On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies") was received on 30 June 1905 and published 26 September of that same year.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] It reconciled conflicts between Maxwell's equations (the laws of electricity and magnetism) and the laws of Newtonian mechanics by introducing changes to the laws of mechanics.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Observationally, the effects of these changes are most apparent at high speeds (where objects are moving at speeds close to the speed of light).
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] The theory developed in this paper later became known as Einstein's special theory of relativity.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] This paper predicted that, when measured in the frame of a relatively moving observer, a clock carried by a moving body would appear to slow down, and the body itself would contract in its direction of motion.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] This paper also argued that the idea of a luminiferous aether—one of the leading theoretical entities in physics at the time—was superfluous.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In his paper on mass–energy equivalence, Einstein produced *E* = *mc*2 as a consequence of his special relativity equations.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's 1905 work on relativity remained controversial for many years, but was accepted by leading physicists, starting with Max Planck.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein originally framed special relativity in terms of kinematics (the study of moving bodies).
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In 1908, Hermann Minkowski reinterpreted special relativity in geometric terms as a theory of spacetime.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein adopted Minkowski's formalism in his 1915 general theory of relativity.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] General relativity (GR) is a theory of gravitation that was developed by Einstein between 1907 and 1915.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] According to it, the observed gravitational attraction between masses results from the warping of spacetime by those masses.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] General relativity has developed into an essential tool in modern astrophysics; it provides the foundation for the current understanding of black holes, regions of space where gravitational attraction is so strong that not even light can escape.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] As Einstein later said, the reason for the development of general relativity was that the preference of inertial motions within special relativity was unsatisfactory, while a theory which from the outset prefers no state of motion (even accelerated ones) should appear more satisfactory.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Consequently, in 1907 he published an article on acceleration under special relativity.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In that article titled "On the Relativity Principle and the Conclusions Drawn from It", he argued that free fall is really inertial motion, and that for a free-falling observer the rules of special relativity must apply.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] This argument is called the equivalence principle.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In the same article, Einstein also predicted the phenomena of gravitational time dilation, gravitational redshift and gravitational lensing.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In 1911, Einstein published another article "On the Influence of Gravitation on the Propagation of Light" expanding on the 1907 article, in which he estimated the amount of deflection of light by massive bodies.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Thus, the theoretical prediction of general relativity could for the first time be tested experimentally.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In 1916, Einstein predicted gravitational waves, ripples in the curvature of spacetime which propagate as waves, traveling outward from the source, transporting energy as gravitational radiation.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] The existence of gravitational waves is possible under general relativity due to its Lorentz invariance which brings the concept of a finite speed of propagation of the physical interactions of gravity with it.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] By contrast, gravitational waves cannot exist in the Newtonian theory of gravitation, which postulates that the physical interactions of gravity propagate at infinite speed.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] The first, indirect, detection of gravitational waves came in the 1970s through observation of a pair of closely orbiting neutron stars, PSR B1913+16.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] The explanation for the decay in their orbital period was that they were emitting gravitational waves.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's prediction was confirmed on 11 February 2016, when researchers at LIGO published the first observation of gravitational waves, detected on Earth on 14 September 2015, nearly one hundred years after the prediction.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] While developing general relativity, Einstein became confused about the gauge invariance in the theory.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] He formulated an argument that led him to conclude that a general relativistic field theory is impossible.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] He gave up looking for fully generally covariant tensor equations and searched for equations that would be invariant under general linear transformations only.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In June 1913, the Entwurf ('draft') theory was the result of these investigations.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] As its name suggests, it was a sketch of a theory, less elegant and more difficult than general relativity, with the equations of motion supplemented by additional gauge fixing conditions.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] After more than two years of intensive work, Einstein realized that the hole argument was mistaken and abandoned the theory in November 1915.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In 1917, Einstein applied the general theory of relativity to the structure of the universe as a whole.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] He discovered that the general field equations predicted a universe that was dynamic, either contracting or expanding.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] As observational evidence for a dynamic universe was lacking at the time, Einstein introduced a new term, the cosmological constant, into the field equations, in order to allow the theory to predict a static universe.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] The modified field equations predicted a static universe of closed curvature, in accordance with Einstein's understanding of Mach's principle in these years.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] This model became known as the Einstein World or Einstein's static universe.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] This paper is widely regarded as marking the emergence of modern theoretical cosmology.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Following the discovery of the recession of the galaxies by Edwin Hubble in 1929, Einstein abandoned his static model of the universe, and proposed two dynamic models of the cosmos, the Friedmann–Einstein universe of 1931 and the Einstein–de Sitter universe of 1932.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In each of these models, Einstein discarded the cosmological constant, claiming that it was "in any case theoretically unsatisfactory".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In many Einstein biographies, it is claimed that Einstein referred to the cosmological constant in later years as his "biggest blunder", based on a letter George Gamow claimed to have received from him.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] The astrophysicist Mario Livio has cast doubt on this claim.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In late 2013, a team led by the Irish physicist Cormac O'Raifeartaigh discovered evidence that, shortly after learning of Hubble's observations of the recession of the galaxies, Einstein considered a steady-state model of the universe.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In a hitherto overlooked manuscript, apparently written in early 1931, Einstein explored a model of the expanding universe in which the density of matter remains constant due to a continuous creation of matter, a process that he associated with the cosmological constant.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] It thus appears that Einstein considered a steady-state model of the expanding universe many years before Hoyle, Bondi and Gold.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] However, Einstein's steady-state model contained a fundamental flaw and he quickly abandoned the idea.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] General relativity includes a dynamical spacetime, so it is difficult to see how to identify the conserved energy and momentum.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Noether's theorem allows these quantities to be determined from a Lagrangian with translation invariance, but general covariance makes translation invariance into something of a gauge symmetry.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] The energy and momentum derived within general relativity by Noether's prescriptions do not make a real tensor for this reason.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein argued that this is true for a fundamental reason: the gravitational field could be made to vanish by a choice of coordinates.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] He maintained that the non-covariant energy momentum pseudotensor was, in fact, the best description of the energy momentum distribution in a gravitational field.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] While the use of non-covariant objects like pseudotensors was criticized by Erwin Schrödinger and others, Einstein's approach has been echoed by physicists including Lev Landau and Evgeny Lifshitz.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In 1935, Einstein collaborated with Nathan Rosen to produce a model of a wormhole, often called Einstein–Rosen bridges.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] His motivation was to model elementary particles with charge as a solution of gravitational field equations, in line with the program outlined in the paper "Do Gravitational Fields play an Important Role in the Constitution of the Elementary Particles?".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] These solutions cut and pasted Schwarzschild black holes to make a bridge between two patches.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Because these solutions included spacetime curvature without the presence of a physical body, Einstein and Rosen suggested that they could provide the beginnings of a theory that avoided the notion of point particles.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] However, it was later found that Einstein–Rosen bridges are not stable.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In order to incorporate spinning point particles into general relativity, the affine connection needed to be generalized to include an antisymmetric part, called the torsion.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] This modification was made by Einstein and Cartan in the 1920s.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In general relativity, gravitational force is reimagined as curvature of spacetime.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] A curved path like an orbit is not the result of a force deflecting a body from an ideal straight-line path, but rather the body's attempt to fall freely through a background that is itself curved by the presence of other masses.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] The geodesic equation covers the former aspect, stating that freely falling bodies follow lines that are as straight as possible in a curved spacetime.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein regarded this as an "independent fundamental assumption" that had to be postulated in addition to the field equations in order to complete the theory.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Believing this to be a shortcoming in how general relativity was originally presented, he wished to derive it from the field equations themselves.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Since the equations of general relativity are non-linear, a lump of energy made out of pure gravitational fields, like a black hole, would move on a trajectory which is determined by the Einstein field equations themselves, not by a new law.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Accordingly, Einstein proposed that the field equations would determine the path of a singular solution, like a black hole, to be a geodesic.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Both physicists and philosophers have often repeated the assertion that the geodesic equation can be obtained from applying the field equations to the motion of a gravitational singularity, but this claim remains disputed.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In a 1905 paper, Einstein postulated that light itself consists of localized particles (*quanta*).
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's light quanta were nearly universally rejected by all physicists, including Max Planck and Niels Bohr.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] This idea only became universally accepted in 1919, with Robert Millikan's detailed experiments on the photoelectric effect, and with the measurement of Compton scattering.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein concluded that each wave of frequency *f* is associated with a collection of photons with energy *hf* each, where *h* is the Planck constant.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] He did not say much more, because he was not sure how the particles were related to the wave.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] But he did suggest that this idea would explain certain experimental results, notably the photoelectric effect.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Light quanta were dubbed *photons* by Gilbert N.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In 1907, Einstein proposed a model of matter where each atom in a lattice structure is an independent harmonic oscillator.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In the Einstein model, each atom oscillates independently—a series of equally spaced quantized states for each oscillator.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein was aware that getting the frequency of the actual oscillations would be difficult, but he nevertheless proposed this theory because it was a particularly clear demonstration that quantum mechanics could solve the specific heat problem in classical mechanics.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In 1924, Einstein received a description of a statistical model from Indian physicist Satyendra Nath Bose, based on a counting method that assumed that light could be understood as a gas of indistinguishable particles.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein noted that Bose's statistics applied to some atoms as well as to the proposed light particles, and submitted his translation of Bose's paper to the *Zeitschrift für Physik*.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein also published his own articles describing the model and its implications, among them the Bose–Einstein condensate phenomenon that some particulates should appear at very low temperatures.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] It was not until 1995 that the first such condensate was produced experimentally by Eric Allin Cornell and Carl Wieman using ultra-cooling equipment built at the NIST–JILA laboratory at the University of Colorado at Boulder.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Bose–Einstein statistics are now used to describe the behaviors of any assembly of bosons.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's sketches for this project may be seen in the Einstein Archive in the library of the Leiden University.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Although the patent office promoted Einstein to Technical Examiner Second Class in 1906, he had not given up on academia.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In 1908, he became a *Privatdozent* at the University of Bern.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] This paper introduced the *photon* concept and inspired the notion of wave–particle duality in quantum mechanics.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein saw this wave–particle duality in radiation as concrete evidence for his conviction that physics needed a new, unified foundation.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In a series of works completed from 1911 to 1913, Planck reformulated his 1900 quantum theory and introduced the idea of zero-point energy in his "second quantum theory".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Soon, this idea attracted the attention of Einstein and his assistant Otto Stern.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Assuming the energy of rotating diatomic molecules contains zero-point energy, they then compared the theoretical specific heat of hydrogen gas with the experimental data.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] However, after publishing the findings, they promptly withdrew their support, because they no longer had confidence in the correctness of the idea of zero-point energy.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In 1917, at the height of his work on relativity, Einstein published an article in *Physikalische Zeitschrift* that proposed the possibility of stimulated emission, the physical process that makes possible the maser and the laser.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] This article showed that the statistics of absorption and emission of light would only be consistent with Planck's distribution law if the emission of light into a mode with n photons would be enhanced statistically compared to the emission of light into an empty mode.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] This paper was enormously influential in the later development of quantum mechanics, because it was the first paper to show that the statistics of atomic transitions had simple laws.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein discovered Louis de Broglie's work and supported his ideas, which were received skeptically at first.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In another major paper from this era, Einstein observed that de Broglie waves could explain the quantization rules of Bohr and Sommerfeld.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] This paper would inspire Schrödinger's work of 1926.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein played a major role in developing quantum theory, beginning with his 1905 paper on the photoelectric effect.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] However, he became displeased with modern quantum mechanics as it had evolved after 1925, despite its acceptance by other physicists.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] He was skeptical that the randomness of quantum mechanics was fundamental rather than the result of determinism, stating that God "is not playing at dice".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Until the end of his life, he continued to maintain that quantum mechanics was incomplete.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] The Bohr–Einstein debates were a series of public disputes about quantum mechanics between Einstein and Niels Bohr, who were two of its founders.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Their debates are remembered because of their importance to the philosophy of science.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Their debates would influence later interpretations of quantum mechanics.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein never fully accepted quantum mechanics.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] While he recognized that it made correct predictions, he believed a more fundamental description of nature must be possible.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Over the years he presented multiple arguments to this effect, but the one he preferred most dated to a debate with Bohr in 1930.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein suggested a thought experiment in which two objects are allowed to interact and then moved apart a great distance from each other.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] The quantum-mechanical description of the two objects is a mathematical entity known as a wavefunction.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] If the wavefunction that describes the two objects before their interaction is given, then the Schrödinger equation provides the wavefunction that describes them after their interaction.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] But because of what would later be called quantum entanglement, measuring one object would lead to an instantaneous change of the wavefunction describing the other object, no matter how far away it is.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Moreover, the choice of which measurement to perform upon the first object would affect what wavefunction could result for the second object.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein reasoned that no influence could propagate from the first object to the second instantaneously fast.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Indeed, he argued, physics depends on being able to tell one thing apart from another, and such instantaneous influences would call that into question.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Because the true "physical condition" of the second object could not be immediately altered by an action done to the first, Einstein concluded, the wavefunction could not be that true physical condition, only an incomplete description of it.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] A more famous version of this argument came in 1935, when Einstein published a paper with Boris Podolsky and Nathan Rosen that laid out what would become known as the EPR paradox.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In this thought experiment, two particles interact in such a way that the wavefunction describing them is entangled.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Then, no matter how far the two particles were separated, a precise position measurement on one particle would imply the ability to predict, perfectly, the result of measuring the position of the other particle.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Likewise, a precise momentum measurement of one particle would result in an equally precise prediction for of the momentum of the other particle, without needing to disturb the other particle in any way.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] They argued that no action taken on the first particle could instantaneously affect the other, since this would involve information being transmitted faster than light, which is forbidden by the theory of relativity.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] But quantum mechanics considers these two observables incompatible and thus does not associate simultaneous values for both to any system.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein, Podolsky, and Rosen therefore concluded that quantum theory does not provide a complete description of reality.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In 1964, John Stewart Bell carried the analysis of quantum entanglement much further.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] He deduced that if measurements are performed independently on the two separated particles of an entangled pair, then the assumption that the outcomes depend upon hidden variables within each half implies a mathematical constraint on how the outcomes on the two measurements are correlated.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] This constraint would later be called a Bell inequality.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Bell then showed that quantum physics predicts correlations that violate this inequality.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Consequently, the only way that hidden variables could explain the predictions of quantum physics is if they are "nonlocal", which is to say that somehow the two particles are able to interact instantaneously no matter how widely they ever become separated.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Bell argued that because an explanation of quantum phenomena in terms of hidden variables would require nonlocality, the EPR paradox "is resolved in the way which Einstein would have liked least".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Despite this, and although Einstein personally found the argument in the EPR paper overly complicated, that paper became among the most influential papers published in *Physical Review*.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] It is considered a centerpiece of the development of quantum information theory.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Encouraged by his success with general relativity, Einstein sought an even more ambitious geometrical theory that would treat gravitation and electromagnetism as aspects of a single entity.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In 1950, he described his unified field theory in a *Scientific American* article titled "On the Generalized Theory of Gravitation".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] His attempt to find the most fundamental laws of nature won him praise but not success: a particularly conspicuous blemish of his model was that it did not accommodate the strong and weak nuclear forces, neither of which was well understood until many years after his death.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Although most researchers now believe that Einstein's approach to unifying physics was mistaken, his goal of a theory of everything is one to which his successors still aspire.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein conducted other investigations that were unsuccessful and abandoned.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] These pertain to force, superconductivity, and other research.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In addition to longtime collaborators Leopold Infeld, Nathan Rosen, Peter Bergmann and others, Einstein also had some one-shot collaborations with various scientists.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In 1908, Owen Willans Richardson predicted that a change in the magnetic moment of a free body will cause this body to rotate.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] This effect is a consequence of the conservation of angular momentum and is strong enough to be observable in ferromagnetic materials.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein and Wander Johannes de Haas published two papers in 1915 claiming the first experimental observation of the effect.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Measurements of this kind demonstrate that the phenomenon of magnetization is caused by the alignment (polarization) of the angular momenta of the electrons in the material along the axis of magnetization.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] These measurements also allow the separation of the two contributions to the magnetization: that which is associated with the spin and with the orbital motion of the electrons.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] The Einstein-de Haas experiment is the only experiment conceived, realized and published by Albert Einstein himself.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] A complete original version of the Einstein-de Haas experimental equipment was donated by Geertruida de Haas-Lorentz, wife of de Haas and daughter of Lorentz, to the Ampère Museum in Lyon France in 1961 where it is currently on display.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] It was lost among the museum's holdings and was rediscovered in 2023.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In 1926, Einstein and his former student Leó Szilárd co-invented (and in 1930, patented) the Einstein refrigerator.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] This absorption refrigerator was then revolutionary for having no moving parts and using only heat as an input.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] On 11 November 1930, U.S. patent 1,781,541 was awarded to Einstein and Leó Szilárd for the refrigerator.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Their invention was not immediately put into commercial production, but the most promising of their patents were acquired by the Swedish company Electrolux.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein also invented an electromagnetic pump, sound reproduction device, and several other household devices.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] While traveling, Einstein wrote daily to his wife Elsa and adopted stepdaughters Margot and Ilse.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] The letters were included in the papers bequeathed to the Hebrew University of Jerusalem.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Margot Einstein permitted the personal letters to be made available to the public, but requested that it not be done until twenty years after her death (she died in 1986).
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Barbara Wolff, of the Hebrew University's Albert Einstein Archives, told the BBC that there are about 3,500 pages of private correspondence written between 1912 and 1955.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In his final four years, Einstein was involved with the establishment of the Albert Einstein College of Medicine in New York City.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In 1979, the Albert Einstein Memorial was unveiled outside the National Academy of Sciences building in Washington, D.C. for the Einstein centenary.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein can be seen holding a paper with three of his most important equations: for the photoelectric effect, general relativity and mass-energy equivalence.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's right of publicity was litigated in 2015 in a federal district court in California.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Although the court initially held that the right had expired, that ruling was immediately appealed, and the decision was later vacated in its entirety.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] The underlying claims between the parties in that lawsuit were ultimately settled.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] The right is enforceable, and the Hebrew University of Jerusalem is the exclusive representative of that right.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Corbis, successor to The Roger Richman Agency, licenses the use of his name and associated imagery, as agent for the university.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Mount Einstein in the Chugach Mountains of Alaska was named in 1955.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Mount Einstein in New Zealand's Paparoa Range was named after him in 1970 by the Department of Scientific and Industrial Research.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In 1999, Einstein was named *Time*'s Person of the Century.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In 1999, a survey of the top 100 physicists voted for Einstein as the "greatest physicist ever", while a parallel survey of rank-and-file physicists gave the top spot to Isaac Newton, with Einstein second.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Simmons ranked Einstein second after Newton in *The Scientific 100*, based on a qualitative assessment in which he ordered the scientists according to overall influence, and noted that the work of Einstein "forms the source of twentieth-century physics".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] The International Union of Pure and Applied Physics declared 2005 the "World Year of Physics", also known as "Einstein Year", in recognition of Einstein's "miracle year" in 1905.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] It was also declared the "International Year of Physics" by the United Nations.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein became one of the most famous scientific celebrities after the confirmation of his general theory of relativity in 1919.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Although most of the public had little understanding of his work, he was widely recognized and admired.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] In the period before World War II, *The New Yorker* published a vignette in their "The Talk of the Town" feature saying that Einstein was so well known in America that he would be stopped on the street by people wanting him to explain "that theory".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Eventually he came to cope with unwanted enquirers by pretending to be someone else: "Pardon me, sorry!
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein has been the subject of or inspiration for many novels, films, plays, and works of music.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] He is a favorite model for depictions of absent-minded professors; his expressive face and distinctive hairstyle have been widely copied and exaggerated.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] *Time* magazine's Frederic Golden wrote that Einstein was "a cartoonist's dream come true".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] His intellectual achievements and originality made *Einstein* broadly synonymous with *genius*.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Many popular quotations are often misattributed to him.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein received numerous awards and honors, and in 1922, he was awarded the 1921 Nobel Prize in Physics "for his services to Theoretical Physics, and especially for his discovery of the law of the photoelectric effect".
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] The Nobel committee decided that none of the nominations in 1921 met the criteria set by Alfred Nobel, so the 1921 prize was carried forward and awarded to Einstein in 1922.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] Einsteinium, a synthetic chemical element, was named in his honor in 1955, a few months after his death.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] (Public Domain) *Einstein, Albert (1926).
[src:american-physical-society/albert-einstein-p04] London & New York: The Encyclopædia Britannica Company. pp.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] He was born on 19 April 1880 in Southington, Connecticut.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] He majored in Greek and after taking one undergraduate course in physics, graduated from Yale University.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] He taught languages at The Albany Academy before returning to Yale, to take a doctorate in physics.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] He then undertook research on photoelectricity whilst teaching physics for five years at the Worcester Polytechnic Institute.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] In 1914 Hull joined the General Electric Research Laboratory (GERL) in Schenectady, New York and remained there until his retirement in 1949.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] During 1916, Hull began investigation into the use of magnetic control of thermionic valves (vacuum tubes) as an alternative to grid or electrostatic control and he had tested successfully magnetic control by applying a magnetic field parallel to the axis of the tube.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] Initially, Hull's work on these novel electron tubes was part of an effort at General Electric to develop amplifiers and oscillators that might be used to circumvent the vacuum- tube triode patents of Lee de Forest and Edwin Armstrong.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] Hull was promoted to assistant director of the GERL in 1928.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] He served as president of the American Physical Society in 1942.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] He retired from General Electric Research Laboratory (GERL) in 1949.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] He did consulting work and served on an advisory committee of the Army Ballistic Research Laboratory after retirement from General Electric.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] He died on 22 January 1966 at the age of 85 in Schenectady, New York.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] He invented the dynatron vacuum tube which had three electrodes: a thermionic cathode, a perforated anode, and a supplementary anode or plate.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] In normal operation the supplementary anode was maintained at a lower positive voltage than the perforated anode.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] The secondary emission of electrons from the plate made the dynatron behave as a true negative resistance and so the tube could generate oscillations over a wide range of frequencies or be used as an amplifier.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] By 1920 his research led to his invention of the magnetron.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] This took the form of a central cathode and a coaxial cylindrical anode split into two halves, with an axial magnetic field produced by an external coil.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] The Hull magnetron was tested as an amplifier in radio receivers and also as a low-frequency oscillator.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] It was reported in 1925 that a magnetron made at GERL could generate a power of 15 kW at a frequency of 20 kHz.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] At the time Hull anticipated that the magnetron would find greater use as a power converter than in communication applications.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] Hull's split-anode magnetron didn't prove to be capable of high frequency or high power output and was little used.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] During WWII John Randall and Harry Boot built on Hull's concept to develop the modern cavity magnetron, the first device which could produce high power at microwave frequencies, and the resulting centimeter-band radar proved a crucial advantage for the Allies in aerial warfare.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] During the 1920s, Hull also was a major contributor to the development of gas-filled electron tubes at the GERL.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] He discovered how to protect thermionic cathodes from rapid disintegration under ion bombardment.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] This discovery enabled the successful development of hot-cathode thyratrons (gaseous triodes) and phanotrons (gaseous diodes).
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] In the 1918 issue of the Proceedings of the IRE he published a paper on the dynatron vacuum tube which he had invented.
[src:american-physical-society/albert-w-hull] During his career in electronics he was the author or coauthor of 72 technical publications and was awarded 94 patents.
[src:american-physical-society/american-association-of-physics-teachers] The **American Association of Physics Teachers** (**AAPT**) was founded in 1930 for the purpose of "dissemination of knowledge of physics, particularly by way of teaching." There are more than 10,000 members in over 30 countries.
[src:american-physical-society/american-association-of-physics-teachers] AAPT publications include two peer-reviewed journals, the *American Journal of Physics* and *The Physics Teacher*.
[src:american-physical-society/american-association-of-physics-teachers] The association has two annual National Meetings (winter and summer) and has regional sections with their own meetings and organization.
[src:american-physical-society/american-association-of-physics-teachers] The association also offers grants and awards for physics educators, including the Richtmyer Memorial Award and programs and contests for physics educators and students.
[src:american-physical-society/american-association-of-physics-teachers] It is headquartered at the American Center for Physics in College Park, Maryland.
[src:american-physical-society/american-association-of-physics-teachers] The American Association of Physics Teachers was founded on December 31, 1930, when forty-five physicists held a meeting during the joint APS-AAAS meeting in Cleveland specifically for that purpose.
[src:american-physical-society/american-association-of-physics-teachers] The AAPT became a founding member of the American Institute of Physics after the other founding members were convinced of the stability of the AAPT itself after a new constitution for the AAPT was agreed upon.
[src:american-physical-society/american-association-of-physics-teachers] The AAPT sponsors a number of competitions for students and educators, including Physics Bowl, Six Flags' roller coaster contest, High School Physics Photo Contest, Apparatus Competition, and the US Physics Team.
[src:american-physical-society/american-association-of-physics-teachers] The US physics team is determined by two preliminary exams and a week and a half long "boot camp".
[src:american-physical-society/american-association-of-physics-teachers] Each year, five members are selected to compete against dozens of countries in the International Physics Olympiad (IPHO).
[src:american-physical-society/american-association-of-physics-teachers] The *American Journal of Physics* is a monthly, peer-reviewed scientific journal published by the American Association of Physics Teachers and the American Institute of Physics.
[src:american-physical-society/american-association-of-physics-teachers] The editor-in-chief is Beth Parks of Colgate University.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] The **American Astronomical Society** (**AAS**, sometimes spoken as "double-A-S") is an American society of professional astronomers and other interested individuals, headquartered in Washington, DC.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] The primary objective of the AAS is to promote the advancement of astronomy and closely related branches of science, while the secondary purpose includes enhancing astronomy education and providing a political voice for its members through lobbying and grassroots activities.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] Its current mission is to enhance and share humanity's scientific understanding of the universe as a diverse and inclusive astronomical community.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] The society was founded in 1899 through the efforts of George Ellery Hale.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] The constitution of the group was written by Hale, George Comstock, Edward Morley, Simon Newcomb and Edward Charles Pickering.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] These men, plus four others, were the first Executive Council of the society; Newcomb was the first president.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] The AAS name of the society was not finally decided until 1915, previously it was the "Astronomical and Astrophysical Society of America".
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] One proposed name that preceded this interim name was "American Astrophysical Society".
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] The membership includes physicists, mathematicians, geologists, engineers and others whose research interests lie within the broad spectrum of subjects now comprising contemporary astronomy.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] The annual meeting of the AAS is held in the spring and constitutes the largest gathering of astronomers, numbering over 3,000 in 2023.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] In 2019 three AAS members were selected into the tenth anniversary class of TED Fellows.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] In January 2025, AAS published a statement calling on nations to ban advertising from space that can be seen from the ground amid growing concern around the launch obtrusive space advertising payloads.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] The AAS is the major organization of professional astronomers in North America.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] The membership includes physicists, mathematicians, geologists, engineers and others whose research interests lie within the broad spectrum of subjects comprising contemporary astronomy.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] The society offers several classes of membership and affiliation.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] Full Members must meet at least two of three criteria: possessing a graduate degree in astronomy or a related science, receiving the nomination of a current Full Member, or having placed a refereed publication in a recognised international journal.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] Until 2018, admission as a Full Member required nomination by two existing Full Members; that year the society restructured its membership classes, broadening eligibility to include holders of master's degrees and introducing new affiliate categories.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] Other membership classes include Graduate Student Members, Undergraduate Student Members (also open to high-school students), International Affiliates for astronomers residing outside the United States, Amateur Affiliates, and Alumni Affiliates for former members who have left the field.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] As of 2025, the AAS has approximately 8,200 members across all categories.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] The society is a member society of the American Institute of Physics.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] The AAS established its Fellows program in 2019 to recognise members for achievement and extraordinary service to the field of astronomy and the society.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] The inaugural class, designated by the AAS Board of Trustees, included 232 Legacy Fellows.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] New fellows are elected annually thereafter.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] Because the field of astronomy is diverse, several divisions have been formed each of which promotes and enables a different branch of astronomy or astronomy-related science as well as working within the overall charter of the AAS.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] Many of the divisions hold separate meetings in addition to meeting with the main group.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] Similar prizes are awarded by AAS divisions.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] The AAS also manages an International Travel Grant program, which any astronomer working in the US may apply to for travel to international astronomy-related conferences and other smaller grant and award programs.
[src:american-physical-society/american-astronomical-society] American Astronomical Society won the 2020 Webby People's Voice Award for Association in the category Web.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] The **American Physical Society** (**APS**) is a not-for-profit membership organization of professionals in physics and related disciplines, comprising nearly fifty divisions, sections, and other units.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] Its mission is the advancement and diffusion of knowledge of physics.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] It publishes more than a dozen scientific journals, including the prestigious *Physical Review* and *Physical Review Letters*, and organizes more than twenty science meetings each year.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] It is a member society of the American Institute of Physics.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] Since January 2021, it is led by chief executive officer Jonathan Bagger.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] The American Physical Society was founded on May 20, 1899, when thirty-six physicists gathered at Columbia University for that purpose.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] They proclaimed the mission of the new Society to be "to advance and diffuse the knowledge of physics", and in one way or another the APS has been at that task ever since.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] In the early years, virtually the sole activity of the APS was to hold scientific meetings, initially four per year.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] In 1913, the APS took over the operation of the *Physical Review,* which had been founded in 1893 at Cornell University, and journal publication became its second major activity.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] The *Physical Review* was followed by *Reviews of Modern Physics* in 1929 and by *Physical Review Letters* in 1958.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] Rev.* has subdivided into five separate sections as the fields of physics proliferated and the number of submissions grew.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] In more recent years, the activities of the society have broadened considerably.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] Stimulated by the increase in federal funding in the period after the Second World War, and even more by the increased public involvement of scientists in the 1960s, the APS is active in public and governmental affairs, and in the international physics community.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] It also conducts extensive programs in education, science outreach (specifically physics outreach), and media relations.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] Fourteen divisions and eleven topical groups covering all areas of physics research.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] Six forums reflect the interests of its fifty thousand members in broader issues, and nine sections organized by geographical region.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] In 1999, APS Physics celebrated its centennial with the biggest-ever physics meeting in Atlanta.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] In 2005, APS took the lead role in United States participation in the World Year of Physics, initiating several programs to broadly publicize physics during the 100th anniversary of Albert Einstein's annus mirabilis.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] Einstein@Home, one of the projects APS initiated during World Year of Physics, is an ongoing and popular distributed computing project.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] During the summer of 2005, the society conducted an electronic poll, in which the majority of APS members preferred the name *American Physics Society*.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] The poll became the motivation for a proposal of a name change promised in the leadership election that year.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] For legal reasons, the planned name change was eventually abandoned by the APS Executive Board.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] APS introduced a new logo to replace the *APS Physics* logo on November 1, 2022.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] The American Physical Society publishes 17 international research journals and an open-access online news and commentary website *Physics*.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] All members of APS receive the monthly publication *Physics Today*, published by the American Institute of Physics (AIP).
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] The American Physical Society has 47 units (divisions, forums, topical groups and sections) that represent the wide range of interests of the physics community.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] The Physics Teacher Education Coalition (PhysTEC) is a joint project of the American Physical Society and the *American Association of Physics Teachers*, which helps universities transform their physics teacher education programs into national models.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] PhysTEC-supported sites develop their physics teacher preparation programs by implementing a set of key components that project leaders have identified as critical to success in physics teacher preparation.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] The broader coalition is a national network of institutions committed to developing and promoting excellence in physics and physical science teacher preparation.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] The APS Bridge Program aims to increase the number of underrepresented minority students that earn doctoral degrees in physics.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] The program names doctoral and master's degree-granting institutions as Bridge Sites and awards them National Science Foundation funding to prepare post-baccalaureate students for doctoral studies through additional coursework, mentoring, research, application coaching, and GRE preparation.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] Formerly called the APS Corporate Sponsored Scholarship Program for Minority Undergraduate Students Who Major in Physics, this scholarship was established in 1980 with the goal of increasing the number of underrepresented minorities receiving bachelor's degrees in physics.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] The program provides funding and mentoring to talented students.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] APS Conferences for Undergraduate Women and Gender Minorities in Physics are three-day regional conferences for undergraduate physics majors.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] The *APS Careers in Physics* website is a gateway for physicists, students, and physics enthusiasts to obtain information about physics jobs and careers.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] APS Careers in Physics has an award-winning job board, offers professional development advice through its website and blog, and provides links to workshops, grants, and career resources.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] APS co-sponsors a set of workshops for new physics and astronomy faculty with the American Association of Physics Teachers and the American Astronomical Society.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] These workshops reach nearly half of all new physics and astronomy faculty, and introduce them to current pedagogical practices, results of physics education research, and time management skills to help them begin and improve their academic careers.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] The APS has had a long-standing interest in improving the climate in physics departments for underrepresented minorities and women.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] The Committee on the Status of Women in Physics (CSWP) and the Committee on Minorities (COM) both sponsor site visit programs to universities as well as national labs.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] APS is a leading voice for physics education and the society sponsors a variety of conferences dedicating to helping physics education leaders stay on top of the trends in the field.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] Conferences include the annual Physics Department Chair Conference, a Graduate Education in Physics Conference, and a Distance Education & Online Learning in Physics Workshop.
[src:american-physical-society/american-physical-society] The American Physical Society gives out a number of awards for research excellence and conduct; topics include outstanding leadership, computational physics, lasers, mathematics, and more.
